      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I see where you're coming from. Let's dive deeper into the goblin's trickery. When the goblin sets up their fake Wi-Fi network, they go to great lengths to make it look like a legitimate hotspot. They might even change the name of their network to something familiar, like \"Free Internet Cafe,\" or use the name of a nearby business that people trust. This way, unsuspecting users might connect to their network, thinking it's safe and secure.\n\nOnce a user connects to the goblin's fake network, the goblin can intercept the data being sent between the user's device and the website they're trying to visit. The goblin then relays this data to the website, pretending to be the user. The website thinks it's talking to the user, but it's actually talking to the goblin.\n\nThe goblin can also modify the data being sent, making it look like it's coming from the user. This way, the website doesn't realize that the goblin is intercepting and relaying the data. It's like the goblin is wearing a disguise, making it hard for the website to tell who's really sending the data.\n\nIt's important to note that this kind of attack requires a lot of technical knowledge and skill. Not every gob",
